1g3.title: Sovereign
1g3.clickbait: The hardest possible class of Friendly AI to build, with the least moral hazard; an AI intended to neither require nor accept further direction.
1g3.text:
In [18k Bostrom]'s [1g0 typology] of [2c advanced agents], a "Sovereign", as distinguished from a "Genie" or an "Oracle", is an AI intended to act freely in the world according to its own preferences and without further direction.  Implicitly, this distinguishes an attemptedly [5s value-aligned] AI that acts this way by design (since failure to solve the alignment problem means the resulting AI is sovereign-by-default).

A Sovereign would be the most difficult possible class of [1g2 Friendly AI] to construct, since it implicitly assumes that we trust the AI more than the [9r programmers] in any conflict between them, and we're okay with removing all constraints and off-switches except those the agent voluntarily takes upon itself.

A *successful* Sovereign would also be the agent design that carries the least moral hazard, since it hands off steering to some fixed [5f preference framework] or objective that the programmers can no longer modify.  Nonetheless, being really really really that sure, not just getting it right but *knowing* we've gotten it right, seems like a large enough problem that perhaps we shouldn't be trying to build this class of AI *for our first try.*

It may seem like this terminology is in danger of being confused with the term "[Singleton](http://www.nickbostrom.com/fut/singleton.html)", but under [intelligence_explosion] scenarios a Singleton seems like a quite probable result of constructing a Sovereign, so in this sense the similarity may be intended.  Nonetheless, the intended meaning of "sovereign" is "self-sovereign and not intrinsically subject to constraint by any higher authority" rather than "sovereign over the universe".
